## Purpose
Performance for a desktop document-processing tool has different constraints than a mobile app.
Forkumentos processes files that can contain thousands of rows, multiple datasources, and complex transformation chains.
This rule defines performance decisions specific to those constraints — not generic optimization tips.

## Scope
Any code that processes collections, reads or writes files, computes derived data, or renders lists with variable item counts.

## Core Principles
- Synchronous file I/O is never permitted on the main thread, regardless of estimated file size.
- Large collections (document rows, template fields, datasource records) are processed lazily or paginated — never loaded entirely into widget tree state at once.
- Expensive computed values are derived via providers that watch the source state — they are never recalculated inside `build()` methods.
- Memory must be explicitly considered when processing datasource files over 10MB. If memory growth is unbounded during processing, the approach is incorrect.
- `const` widgets are used everywhere structurally possible — but their primary justification is correctness and expressiveness, not micro-optimization.

## DO
- Use `Isolate` or `compute()` for CPU-heavy transformations (e.g., applying a transformation chain to 50,000 rows).
- Use `ListView.builder` or `TableView` for any list whose item count exceeds 100 items.
- Cancel in-flight async operations when the provider is disposed (use `ref.onDispose` to cancel).
- Stream file reads line-by-line when the total file size is unknown at load time.

## DON'T
- Read an entire CSV or JSON file into a `String` before parsing if the file can be large.
- Rebuild a full list widget when only one item changes — use targeted provider watches.
- Store a computed collection (filtered list, sorted result) as a field on a notifier — use a derived provider instead.

## NEVER
- Block the main thread with synchronous disk access, even for "small" configuration files.
- Load a full datasource file into memory inside a widget's `initState`.

## GOOD Example
```dart
// Derived sorted list — never stored in notifier state
final sortedTemplateListProvider = Provider<List<Template>>((ref) {
  final templates = ref.watch(templateListProvider);
  return [...templates]..sort((a, b) => a.name.compareTo(b.name));
});
```

## BAD Example
```dart
// Synchronous file read — never acceptable on main thread
final content = File(path).readAsStringSync();
```

## Decision Rules
Will this operation touch the file system? → Make it async, run off main thread.
Will this operation produce a derived collection? → Make it a `Provider`, not a notifier field.
Does the list have more than 100 items? → Use a virtualized list widget.
Is memory growth bounded? → If not, stop and redesign the approach.

## Conflict Resolution
This rule takes precedence over `ui_philosophy.mdc` when there is a conflict between user feedback immediacy and performance correctness. A correct slow response with progress indication is preferred over a fast response that blocks the thread.
